hp?title=Culture_of_the_Song_dynasty&amp;action=edit"/>\n<link rel="apple-touch-icon" href="/static/apple-touch/wikipedia.png"/>\n<link rel="shortcut icon" href="/static/favicon/wikipedia.ico"/>\n<link rel="search" type="application/opensearchdescription+xml" href="/w/opensearch_desc.php" title="Wikipedia (en)"/>\n<link rel="EditURI" type="application/rsd+xml" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd"/>\n<link rel="license" href="//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/"/>\n<link rel="canonical" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Culture_of_the_Song_dynasty"/>\n<link rel="dns-prefetch" href="//login.wikimedia.org"/>\n<link rel="dns-prefetch" href="//meta.wikimedia.org" />\n<!--[if lt IE 9]><script src="/resources/lib/html5shiv/html5shiv.min.js"></script><![endif]-->\n</head>\n<body class="mediawiki ltr sitedir-ltr mw-hide-empty-elt ns-0 ns-subject page-Culture_of_the_Song_dynasty rootpage-Culture_of_the_Song_dynasty skin-vector action-view">\t\t<div id="mw-page-base" class="noprint"></div>\n\t\t<div id="mw-head-base" class="noprint"></div>\n\t\t<div id="content" class="mw-body" role="main">\n\t\t\t<a id="top"></a>\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div id="siteNotice" class="mw-body-content"><!-- CentralNotice --></div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class="mw-indicators mw-body-content">\n<div id="mw-indicator-good-star" class="mw-indicator"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Good_articles" title="This is a good article. Click here for more information."><img alt="This is a good article. Click here for more information." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/94/Symbol_support_vote.svg/19px-Symbol_support_vote.svg.png" width="19" height="20" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/94/Symbol_support_vote.svg/29px-Symbol_support_vote.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/94/Symbol_support_vote.svg/39px-Symbol_support_vote.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="180" data-file-height="185" /></a></div>\n</div>\n\t\t\t<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en">Culture of the Song dynasty</h1>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div id="bodyContent" class="mw-body-content">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div id="siteSub" class="noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div id="contentSub"></div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div id="jump-to-nav" class="mw-jump">\n\t\t\t\t\tJump to:\t\t\t\t\t<a href="#mw-head">navigation</a>, \t\t\t\t\t<a href="#p-search">search</a>\n\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t\t\t<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><div class="mw-parser-output"><div class="thumb tright">\n<div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Inkstone.jpg" class="image"><img alt="A black, rectangular stone tablet with two sections. The top quarter section contains a carving of a fish, and the bottom three fourths contain a shallow, circular indent for the ink." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/Inkstone.jpg/200px-Inkstone.jpg" width="200" height="303" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/Inkstone.jpg/300px-Inkstone.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/Inkstone.jpg/400px-Inkstone.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1992" data-file-height="3018" /></a>\n<div class="thumbcaption">\n<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Inkstone.jpg" class="internal" title="Ingrandisci"></a></div>\nA <a href="/wiki/Song_dynasty" title="Song dynasty">Song dynasty</a> <a href="/wiki/Chinese_inkstone" class="mw-redirect" title="Chinese inkstone">Chinese inkstone</a> with gold and silver markings, from the Nantoy\xc5\x8ds\xc5\x8d Collection, <a href="/wiki/Japan" title="Japan">Japan</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>The <a href="/wiki/Song_dynasty" title="Song dynasty">Song dynasty</a> (960\xe2\x80\x931279 AD) was a culturally rich and sophisticated age for <a href="/wiki/China" title="China">China</a>. There was blossoming of and advancements in the visual arts, music, literature, and philosophy. Officials of the ruling bureaucracy, who underwent a strict and extensive examination process, reached new heights of education in Chinese society, while general Chinese culture was enhanced by widespread printing, growing literacy, and various arts.</p>\n<p>Appreciation of art among the <a href="/wiki/Gentry_(China)" class="mw-redirect" title="Gentry (China)">gentry class</a> flourished during the Song dynasty, especially in regard to paintings, which is an art practiced by many. Trends in painting styles amongst the gentry notably shifted from the Northern (960\xe2\x80\x931127) to Southern Song (1127\xe2\x80\x931279) periods, influenced in part by the gradual embrace of the <a href="/wiki/Neo-Confucianism" title="Neo-Confucianism">Neo-Confucian</a> political ideology at court.</p>\n<p>People in urban areas enjoyed <a href="/wiki/Chinese_opera" title="Chinese opera">theatrical drama on stage</a>, restaurants that catered to a variety of regional cooking, lavish clothing and apparel sold in the markets, while both urban and rural people engaged in <a href="/wiki/Traditional_Chinese_holidays" title="Traditional Chinese holidays">seasonal festivities and religious holidays</a>.</p>\n<p></p>\n<div id="toc" class="toc">\n<div class="toctitle">\n<h2>Contents</h2>\n</div>\n<ul>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-1"><a href="#Visual_arts"><span class="tocnumber">1</span> <span class="toctext">Visual arts</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-2"><a href="#Paintings"><span class="tocnumber">1.1</span> <span class="toctext">Paintings</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-3"><a href="#Ceramics"><span class="tocnumber">1.2</span> <span class="toctext">Ceramics</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-4"><a href="#Sculpture"><span class="tocnumber">1.3</span> <span class="toctext">Sculpture</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-5"><a href="#Poetry_and_literature"><span class="tocnumber">2</span> <span class="toctext">Poetry and literature</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-6"><a href="#Performing_arts"><span class="tocnumber">3</span> <span class="toctext">Performing arts</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-7"><a href="#Festivities"><span class="tocnumber">4</span> <span class="toctext">Festivities</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-8"><a href="#Clothing_and_apparel"><span class="tocnumber">5</span> <span class="toctext">Clothing and apparel</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-9"><a href="#Food_and_cuisine"><span class="tocnumber">6</span> <span class="toctext">Food and cuisine</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-10"><a href="#Philosophy"><span class="tocnumber">7</span> <span class="toctext">Philosophy</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-11"><a href="#See_also"><span class="tocnumber">8</span> <span class="toctext">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-12"><a href="#Notes"><span class="tocnumber">9</span> <span class="toctext">Notes</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-13"><a href="#References"><span class="tocnumber">10</span> <span class="toctext">References</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-14"><a href="#Further_reading"><span class="tocnumber">11</span> <span class="toctext">Further reading</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-15"><a href="#External_links"><span class="tocnumber">12</span> <span class="toctext">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<p></p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Visual_arts">Visual arts</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Culture_of_the_Song_dynasty&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Visual arts">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Further information: <a href="/wiki/Chinese_art" title="Chinese art">Chinese art</a>, <a href="/wiki/History_of_Chinese_art" class="mw-redirect" title="History of Chinese art">History of Chinese art</a>, <a href="/wiki/Chinese_painting" title="Chinese painting">Chinese painting</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Chinese_ceramics" title="Chinese ceramics">Chinese ceramics</a></div>\n<div class="thumb tright">\n<div class="thumbinner" style="width:207px;"><a href="/wiki/File:CaiWenji-return150dpi90_percent.jpg" class="image"><img alt="A faded painting with three people on two horses. The nearer horse is black, and a man sits on it facing the farther horse. The farther horse is white and a woman sits on it, holding a small child." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/21/CaiWenji-return150dpi90_percent.jpg/205px-CaiWenji-return150dpi90_percent.jpg" width="205" height="215" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/21/CaiWenji-return150dpi90_percent.jpg/308px-CaiWenji-return150dpi90_percent.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/21/CaiWenji-return150dpi90_percent.jpg/410px-CaiWenji-return150dpi90_percent.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1050" data-file-height="1101" /></a>\n<div class="thumbcaption">\n<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:CaiWenji-return150dpi90_percent.jpg" class="internal" title="Ingrandisci"></a></div>\nAnonymous painting of <a href="/wiki/Cai_Wenji" class="mw-redirect" title="Cai Wenji">Cai Wenji</a> and her <a href="/wiki/Xiongnu" title="Xiongnu">Xiongnu</a> husband (Zuoxianwang) dating from the Southern Song.</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p><a href="/wiki/Chinese_painting" title="Chinese painting">Chinese painting</a> during the Song dynasty reached a new level of sophistication with further development of <a href="/wiki/Landscape_painting" title="Landscape painting">landscape painting</a>. The <i><a href="/wiki/Shan_shui" title="Shan shui">shan shui</a></i> style painting\xe2\x80\x94"shan" meaning mountain, and "shui" meaning river\xe2\x80\x94became prominent features in Chinese landscape art. The emphasis laid upon landscape painting in the Song period was grounded in <a href="/wiki/Chinese_philosophy" title="Chinese philosophy">Chinese philosophy</a>; <a href="/wiki/Taoism" title="Taoism">Taoism</a> stressed that humans were but tiny specks amongst vast and greater cosmos, while <a href="/wiki/Neo-Confucianist" class="mw-redirect" title="Neo-Confucianist">Neo-Confucianist</a> writers often pursued the discovery of patterns and principles that they believed caused all social and natural phenomena.<sup id="cite_ref-ebrey_cambridge_162_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ebrey_cambridge_162-1">[1]</a></sup> The making of glazed and translucent porcelain and celadon wares with complex use of <a href="/wiki/Vitreous_enamel" title="Vitreous enamel">enamels</a> was also developed further during the Song period. <a href="/wiki/Longquan_celadon" title="Longquan celadon">Longquan celadon</a> wares were particularly popular in the Song period. Black and red <a href="/wiki/Lacquerware" title="Lacquerware">lacquerwares</a> of the Song period featured beautifully carved artwork of miniature nature scenes, landscapes, or simple decorative <a href="/wiki/Motif_(visual_arts)" title="Motif (visual arts)">motifs</a>. However, even though intricate bronze-casting, ceramics and lacquerware, jade carving, sculpture, architecture, and the painting of portraits and closely viewed objects like birds on branches were held in high esteem by the Song Chinese, landscape painting was paramount.<sup id="cite_ref-morton_104_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-morton_104-2">[2]</a></sup> By the beginning of the Song dynasty a distinctive <a href="/wiki/Northern_Landscape_style" class="mw-redirect" title="Northern Landscape style">landscape style</a> had emerged.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup> Artists mastered the formula of creating intricate and realistic scenes placed in the foreground, while the background retained qualities of vast and infinite space. Distant mountain peaks rise out of high clouds and mist, while streaming rivers run from afar into the foreground.<sup id="cite_ref-morton_105_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-morton_105-4">[4]</a></sup></p>\n<div class="thumb tleft">\n<div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Song_Dynasty_Porcelain_Bottle.jpg" class="image"><img alt="A handle-less jug which has a small bottom, a wide middle, and a very small opening at the top. The jug is white porcelain with a tan illustration of leaves or a vine wrapping around the entirety of the jug." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Song_Dynasty_Porcelain_Bottle.jpg/170px-Song_Dynasty_Porcelain_Bottle.jpg" width="170" height="197" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Song_Dynasty_Porcelain_Bottle.jpg/255px-Song_Dynasty_Porcelain_Bottle.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Song_Dynasty_Porcelain_Bottle.jpg/340px-Song_Dynasty_Porcelain_Bottle.jpg 2x" data-file-width="765" data-file-height="885" /></a>\n<div class="thumbcaption">\n<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Song_Dynasty_Porcelain_Bottle.jpg" class="internal" title="Ingrandisci"></a></div>\nSong <a href="/wiki/Ding_ware" title="Ding ware">ding ware</a> <a href="/wiki/Porcelain" title="Porcelain">porcelain</a> bottle, 11th century.</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>There was a significant difference in painting trends between the Northern Song period (960\xe2\x80\x931127) and Southern Song period (1127\xe2\x80\x931279). The paintings of Northern Song officials were influenced by their political ideals of bringing order to the world and tackling the largest issues affecting the whole of their society, hence their paintings often depicted huge, sweeping landscapes.<sup id="cite_ref-ebrey_cambridge_163_5-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ebrey_cambridge_163-5">[5]</a></sup> On the other hand, Southern Song officials were more interested in reforming society from the bottom up and on a much smaller scale, a method they believed had a better chance for eventual success.<sup id="cite_ref-ebrey_cambridge_163_5-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ebrey_cambridge_163-5">[5]</a></sup> Hence, their paintings often focused on smaller, visually closer, and more intimate scenes, while the background was often depicted as bereft of detail as a realm without substance or concern for the artist or viewer.<sup id="cite_ref-ebrey_cambridge_163_5-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ebrey_cambridge_163-5">[5]</a></sup> This change in attitude from one era to the next stemmed largely from the rising influence of <a href="/wiki/Neo-Confucianism" title="Neo-Confucianism">Neo-Confucian</a> philosophy. Adherents to Neo-Confucianism focused on reforming society from the bottom up, not the top down, which can be seen in their efforts to promote small private academies during the Southern Song instead of the large state-controlled academies seen in the Northern Song era.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup></p>\n<div class="thumb tright">\n<div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Verseuse_ph%C3%A9nix_Mus%C3%A9e_Guimet_2418.jpg" class="image"><img alt="A green jug which is small at the bottom, wide near the middle, and has a tall, narrow opening at the top. The jug has a handle on one side and a carved bird head on the other side, bot connected to the top of the jug. The body of the jug has a flower or leaf pattern carved into it." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/11/Verseuse_ph%C3%A9nix_Mus%C3%A9e_Guimet_2418.jpg/170px-Verseuse_ph%C3%A9nix_Mus%C3%A9e_Guimet_2418.jpg" width="170" height="223" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/11/Verseuse_ph%C3%A9nix_Mus%C3%A9e_Guimet_2418.jpg/255px-Verseuse_ph%C3%A9nix_Mus%C3%A9e_Guimet_2418.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/11/Verseuse_ph%C3%A9nix_Mus%C3%A9e_Guimet_2418.jpg/340px-Verseuse_ph%C3%A9nix_Mus%C3%A9e_Guimet_2418.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1514" data-file-height="1984" /></a>\n<div class="thumbcaption">\n<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Verseuse_ph%C3%A9nix_Mus%C3%A9e_Guimet_2418.jpg" class="internal" title="Ingrandisci"></a></div>\nA vase with a <a href="/wiki/Chinese_phoenix" class="mw-redirect" title="Chinese phoenix">phoenix-headed</a> spout, gray sandstone with celadon coating, 10th century.</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>Ever since the <a href="/wiki/Southern_and_Northern_Dynasties" class="mw-redirect" title="Southern and Northern Dynasties">Southern and Northern Dynasties</a> (420\xe2\x80\x93589), painting had become an art of high sophistication that was associated with the gentry class as one of their main artistic pastimes, the others being calligraphy and poetry.<sup id="cite_ref-ebrey_81_83_7-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ebrey_81_83-7">[7]</a></sup> During the Song dynasty there were avid art collectors that would often meet in groups to discuss their own paintings, as well as rate those of their colleagues and friends. The poet and statesman <a href="/wiki/Su_Shi" title="Su Shi">Su Shi</a> (1037\xe2\x80\x931101) and his accomplice <a href="/wiki/Mi_Fu" title="Mi Fu">Mi Fu</a> (1051\xe2\x80\x931107) often partook in these affairs, borrowing art pieces to study and copy, or if they really admired a piece then an exchange was often proposed.<sup id="cite_ref-ebrey_163_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ebrey_163-8">[8]</a></sup> The small round paintings popular in the Southern Song were often collected into albums as poets would write poems along the side to match the theme and mood of the painting.<sup id="cite_ref-ebrey_cambridge_163_5-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ebrey_cambridge_163-5">[5]</a></sup></p>\n<p>Although they were avid art collectors, some Song scholars did not readily appreciate artworks commissioned by those painters found at shops or common marketplaces, and some of the scholars even criticized artists from renowned schools and academies. Anthony J. Barbieri-Low, a Professor of Early Chinese History at the <a href="/wiki/University_of_California,_Santa_Barbara" title="University of California, Santa Barbara">University of California, Santa Barbara</a>, points out that Song scholars\' appreciation of art created by their peers was not extended to those who made a living simply as professional artists:<sup id="cite_ref-barbieri_low_2007_39_40_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-barbieri_low_2007_39_40-9">[9]</a></sup></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>During the Northern Song (960\xe2\x80\x931126 CE), a new class of scholar-artists emerged who did not possess the tromp l\'oiel skills of the academy painters nor even the proficiency of common marketplace painters. The literati\'s painting was simpler and at times quite unschooled, yet they would criticize these other two groups as mere professionals, since they relied on paid commissions for their livelihood and did not paint merely for enjoyment or self-expression. The scholar-artists considered that painters who concentrated on realistic depictions, who employed a colorful palette, or, worst of all, who accepted monetary payment for their work were no better than butchers or tinkers in the marketplace. They were not to be considered real artists.<sup id="cite_ref-barbieri_low_2007_39_40_9-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-barbieri_low_2007_39_40-9">[9]</a></sup></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>However, during the Song period, there were many acclaimed court painters and they were highly esteemed by emperors and the <a href="/wiki/Royal_family" title="Royal family">royal family</a>. One of the greatest landscape painters given patronage by the Song court was <a href="/wiki/Zhang_Zeduan" title="Zhang Zeduan">Zhang Zeduan</a> (1085\xe2\x80\x931145), who painted the original <i><a href="/wiki/Along_the_River_During_Qingming_Festival" class="mw-redirect" title="Along the River During Qingming Festival">Along the River During Qingming Festival</a></i> scroll, one of the most well-known masterpieces of Chinese visual art. <a href="/wiki/Emperor_Gaozong_of_Song" title="Emperor Gaozong of Song">Emperor Gaozong of Song</a> (1127\xe2\x80\x931162) once commissioned an art project of numerous paintings for the <i><a href="/wiki/Eighteen_Songs_of_a_Nomad_Flute" title="Eighteen Songs of a Nomad Flute">Eighteen Songs of a Nomad Flute</a></i>, based on the woman poet <a href="/wiki/Cai_Wenji" class="mw-redirect" title="Cai Wenji">Cai Wenji</a> (177\xe2\x80\x93250 AD) of the earlier <a href="/wiki/Han_dynasty" title="Han dynasty">Han dynasty</a>. The Southern Song dynasty court painters included Zhao Mengjian (\xe8\xb6\x99\xe5\xad\x9f\xe5\xa0\x85, c.1199\xe2\x80\x931264), a member of the Imperial family, known for popularising the <a href="/wiki/Three_Friends_of_Winter" title="Three Friends of Winter">Three Friends of Winter</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Mengjian_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Mengjian-10">[10]</a></sup></p>\n<p>During the Song period Buddhism saw a small revival since its persecution during the Tang dynasty. This could be seen in the continued construction of sculpture artwork at the <a href="/wiki/Dazu_Rock_Carvings" title="Dazu Rock Carvings">Dazu Rock Carvings</a> in <a href="/wiki/Sichuan" title="Sichuan">Sichuan</a> province. Similar in design to the sculptures at Dazu, the Song temple at Mingshan in <a href="/wiki/Anyue" class="mw-redirect" title="Anyue">Anyue</a>, Sichuan province features a wealth of Song era Buddhist sculptures, including the Buddha and deities clad in lavish imperial and monastic robes.<sup id="cite_ref-sorensen_282-283_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sorensen_282-283-11">[11]</a></sup></p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Paintings">Paintings</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Culture_of_the_Song_dynasty&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Paintings">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<ul class="gallery mw-gallery-traditional center">\n<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 175px">\n<div style="width: 175px">\n<div class="thumb" style="width: 170px;">\n<div style="margin:15px auto;"><a href="/wiki/File:Cui_Bai_-_Magpies_and_Hare.jpg" class="image"><img alt="A long, portrait oriented painting. To the right is a small hill with a tree protruding from it. Two birds are swooping in from the upper right corner, one passing in front of the tree. In the bottom left corner is a hare with its head tilted upwards, facing the birds. The scroll uses dark inks, and has darkened and become orange with age." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/Cui_Bai_-_Magpies_and_Hare.jpg/74px-Cui_Bai_-_Magpies_and_Hare.jpg" width="74" height="140" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/Cui_Bai_-_Magpies_and_Hare.jpg/112px-Cui_Bai_-_Magpies_and_Hare.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/Cui_Bai_-_Magpies_and_Hare.jpg/149px-Cui_Bai_-_Magpies_and_Hare.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1776" data-file-height="3335" /></a></div>\n</div>\n<div class="gallerytext">\n<p><i>Magpies and Hare</i>, signed and dated by <a href="/wiki/Cui_Bai" title="Cui Bai">Cui Bai</a>, latter 11th century.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</li>\n<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 175px">\n<div style="width: 175px">\n<div class="thumb" style="width: 170px;">\n<div style="margin:15px auto;"><a href="/wiki/File:Su_Han_Ch%27en_001.jpg" class="image"><img alt="A portrait oriented painting depicting two young children, a boy and a slightly older girl, playing with figurines on a table in a garden. Behind them is a tall rock flanked by branches of a flowering tree." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c0/Su_Han_Ch%27en_001.jpg/76px-Su_Han_Ch%27en_001.jpg" width="76" height="140" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c0/Su_Han_Ch%27en_001.jpg/115px-Su_Han_Ch%27en_001.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c0/Su_Han_Ch%27en_001.jpg/153px-Su_Han_Ch%27en_001.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1256" data-file-height="2295" /></a></div>\n</div>\n<div class="gallerytext">\n<p><i>Playing Children</i>, by Su Han Chen, 1150.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</li>\n<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 175px">\n<div style="width: 175px">\n<div class="thumb" style="width: 170px;">\n<div style="margin:16px auto;"><a href="/wiki/File:Mao_I_001.jpg" class="image"><img alt="A square painting depicting four cats, two in the bottom left tussling and two on the bottom right not doing anything in particular, in a garden with small flowering bushes." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0a/Mao_I_001.jpg/140px-Mao_I_001.jpg" width="140" height="138" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0a/Mao_I_001.jpg/210px-Mao_I_001.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0a/Mao_I_001.jpg/280px-Mao_I_001.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2024" data-file-height="1996" /></a></div>\n</div>\n<div class="gallerytext">\n<p><i>Cats in the Garden</i>, by Mao Yi, 12th century.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</li>\n<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 175px">\n<div style="width: 175px">\n<div class="thumb" style="width: 170px;">\n<div style="margin:15px auto;"><a href="/wiki/File:Fan_Kuan_-_Travelers_Among_Mountains_and_Streams_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg" class="image"><img alt="A long, portrait oriented scroll depicting a very tall mountain in the background and a stream with trees in the foreground, near the bottom of the painting. Contrary to the name of the painting, there are no travelers shown." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Fan_Kuan_-_Travelers_Among_Mountains_and_Streams_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg/70px-Fan_Kuan_-_Travelers_Among_Mountains_and_Streams_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg" width="70" height="140" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Fan_Kuan_-_Travelers_Among_Mountains_and_Streams_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg/104px-Fan_Kuan_-_Travelers_Among_Mountains_and_Streams_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Fan_Kuan_-_Travelers_Among_Mountains_and_Streams_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg/139px-Fan_Kuan_-_Travelers_Among_Mountains_and_Streams_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2809" data-file-height="5633" /></a></div>\n</div>\n<div class="gallerytext">\n<p><i>Travelers among Mountains and Streams</i>, by <a href="/wiki/Fan_Kuan" title="Fan Kuan">Fan Kuan</a>, 11th century</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</li>\n<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 175px">\n<div style="width: 175px">\n<div class="thumb" style="width: 170px;">\n<div style="margin:15.5px auto;"><a href="/wiki/File:Loquats_and_Mountain_Bird.jpg" class="image"><img alt="A square painting depiciting a small bird, with a grey top and white underbelly, perched on a branch that ends with a large cluster of orange tinted fruits, each about half the size of the bird." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/17/Loquats_and_Mountain_Bird.jpg/140px-Loquats_and_Mountain_Bird.jpg" width="140" height="139" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/17/Loquats_and_Mountain_Bird.jpg/210px-Loquats_and_Mountain_Bird.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/17/Loquats_and_Mountain_Bird.jpg/280px-Loquats_and_Mountain_Bird.jpg 2x" data-file-width="468" data-file-height="465" /></a></div>\n</div>\n<div class="gallerytext">\n<p><i><a href="/wiki/Loquats" class="mw-redirect" title="Loquats">Loquats</a> and Mountain Bird</i>, anonymous painter of the Southern Song</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</li>\n<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 175px">\n<div style="width: 175px">\n<div class="thumb" style="width: 170px;">\n<div style="margin:15px auto;"><a href="/wiki/File:Li_Anzhong%27s_Bird_on_a_Branch.gif" class="image"><img alt="A square painting with irregularly sloped curved corners depicting a puffy bird with a blue-grey back and white underbelly perching on top of a bamboo branch." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Li_Anzhong%27s_Bird_on_a_Branch.gif/140px-Li_Anzhong%27s_Bird_on_a_Branch.gif" width="140" height="140" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Li_Anzhong%27s_Bird_on_a_Branch.gif/210px-Li_Anzhong%27s_Bird_on_a_Branch.gif 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Li_Anzhong%27s_Bird_on_a_Branch.gif/280px-Li_Anzhong%27s_Bird_on_a_Branch.gif 2x" data-file-width="504" data-file-height="504" /></a></div>\n</div>\n<div class="gallerytext">\n<p><i>Bird on a Branch</i>, Li Anzhong, early-mid 12th century</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</li>\n<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 175px">\n<div style="width: 175px">\n<div class="thumb" style="width: 170px;">\n<div style="margin:20px auto;"><a href="/wiki/File:Song_Duckling.jpg" class="image"><img alt="A square painting of a duckling with a grey back, white underbelly, and yellow tinted face. The duckling is looking down towards the lower, right hand corner." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b6/Song_Duckling.jpg/140px-Song_Duckling.jpg" width="140" height="130" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b6/Song_Duckling.jpg/210px-Song_Duckling.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b6/Song_Duckling.jpg/280px-Song_Duckling.jpg 2x" data-file-width="468" data-file-height="435" /></a></div>\n</div>\n<div class="gallerytext">\n<p>A duckling, anonymous painter of the Southern Song</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</li>\n<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 175px">\n<div style="width: 175px">\n<div class="thumb" style="width: 170px;">\n<div style="margin:16px auto;"><a href="/wiki/File:Song_Palace_Children_Playing.jpg" class="image"><img alt="A square painting of four well dressed small boys playing in a circle. Unused toys sit in a corner. The background uses darker colors while the children are wearing mostly white and bright colors." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e5/Song_Palace_Children_Playing.jpg/140px-Song_Palace_Children_Playing.jpg" width="140" height="138" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e5/Song_Palace_Children_Playing.jpg/210px-Song_Palace_Children_Playing.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e5/Song_Palace_Children_Playing.jpg/280px-Song_Palace_Children_Playing.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1280" data-file-height="1263" /></a></div>\n</div>\n<div class="gallerytext">\n<p>Palace children playing, Northern or Southern Song</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</li>\n<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 175px">\n<div style="width: 175px">\n<div class="thumb" style="width: 170px;">\n<div style="margin:15px auto;"><a href="/wiki/File:Guo_Xi_-_Early_Spring_(large).jpg" class="image"><img alt="A landscape oriented painting of gnarled looking trees on top of wavy mountaintops. A large collection or square, red seal stamps are arranged at the corners and edges of the work." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/86/Guo_Xi_-_Early_Spring_%28large%29.jpg/96px-Guo_Xi_-_Early_Spring_%28large%29.jpg" width="96" height="140" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/86/Guo_Xi_-_Early_Spring_%28large%29.jpg/144px-Guo_Xi_-_Early_Spring_%28large%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/86/Guo_Xi_-_Early_Spring_%28large%29.jpg/192px-Guo_Xi_-_Early_Spring_%28large%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1952" data-file-height="2839" /></a></div>\n</div>\n<div class="gallerytext">\n<p><i><a href="/wiki/Early_Spring_(painting)" title="Early Spring (painting)">Early Spring</a></i>, by <a href="/wiki/Guo_Xi" title="Guo Xi">Guo Xi</a> (c. 1020\xe2\x80\x931090), 1072.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</li>\n<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 175px">\n<div style="width: 175px">\n<div class="thumb" style="width: 170px;">\n<div style="margin:26.5px auto;"><a href="/wiki/File:Zhang_Shengwen._L%27enseignement_de_Bouddha_Sakyamuni.jpg" class="image"><img alt="A landscape oriented painting showing a Buddha in red robes, seated in a throne, surrounded by sixteen adult figures and one baby. With the exception of the baby, all of the figures, including the Buddha, have blue halos." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Zhang_Shengwen._L%27enseignement_de_Bouddha_Sakyamuni.jpg/140px-Zhang_Shengwen._L%27enseignement_de_Bouddha_Sakyamuni.jpg" width="140" height="117" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Zhang_Shengwen._L%27enseignement_de_Bouddha_Sakyamuni.jpg/210px-Zhang_Shengwen._L%27enseignement_de_Bouddha_Sakyamuni.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Zhang_Shengwen._L%27enseignement_de_Bouddha_Sakyamuni.jpg/280px-Zhang_Shengwen._L%27enseignement_de_Bouddha_Sakyamuni.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2024" data-file-height="1688" /></a></div>\n</div>\n<div class="gallerytext">\n<p><i>The <a href="/wiki/Sakyamuni" class="mw-redirect" title="Sakyamuni">Sakyamuni</a> <a href="/wiki/Buddhahood" title="Buddhahood">Buddha</a></i>, by Zhang Shengwen, c. 1173\xe2\x80\x931176</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</li>\n<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 175px">\n<div style="width: 175px">\n<div class="thumb" style="width: 170px;">\n<div style="margin:70px auto;"><a href="/wiki/File:Songhuizong5.jpg" class="image"><img alt="A long, landscape oriented painting. On the right half are several white birds flocking around the roof of a building. On the left half is a block of vertically oriented text." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/67/Songhuizong5.jpg/140px-Songhuizong5.jpg" width="140" height="30" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/67/Songhuizong5.jpg/210px-Songhuizong5.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/67/Songhuizong5.jpg/280px-Songhuizong5.jpg 2x" data-file-width="4959" data-file-height="1064" /></a></div>\n</div>\n<div class="gallerytext">\n<p>Painting by <a href="/wiki/Emperor_Huizong_of_Song" title="Emperor Huizong of Song">Emperor Huizong of Song</a>, a renowned scholar and painter, 1112</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</li>\n<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 175px">\n<div style="width: 175px">\n<div class="thumb" style="width: 170px;">\n<div style="margin:15px auto;"><a href="/wiki/File:Chinesischer_Maler_des_11._Jahrhunderts_(III)_001.jpg" class="image"><img alt="A long, portrait oriented painting of a bare-chested, bearded man sitting on a mat under a tree, reading." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ed/Chinesischer_Maler_des_11._Jahrhunderts_%28III%29_001.jpg/85px-Chinesischer_Maler_des_11._Jahrhunderts_%28III%29_001.jpg" width="85" height="140" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ed/Chinesischer_Maler_des_11._Jahrhunderts_%28III%29_001.jpg/127px-Chinesischer_Maler_des_11._Jahrhunderts_%28III%29_001.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ed/Chinesischer_Maler_des_11._Jahrhunderts_%28III%29_001.jpg/170px-Chinesischer_Maler_des_11._Jahrhunderts_%28III%29_001.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1256" data-file-height="2070" /></a></div>\n</div>\n<div class="gallerytext">\n<p><i>A Scholar in a Meadow</i>, 11th century.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</li>\n<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 175px">\n<div style="width: 175px">\n<div class="thumb" style="width: 170px;">\n<div style="margin:15px auto;"><a href="/wiki/File:Chinesischer_Maler_des_11._Jahrhunderts_(II)_001.jpg" class="image"><img alt="A portrait oriented painting depicting a six armed figure with a red halo sitting inside of a white lotus flower. The flower is resting on the back of a peacock, whose tail feathers are fully extended." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Chinesischer_Maler_des_11._Jahrhunderts_%28II%29_001.jpg/85px-Chinesischer_Maler_des_11._Jahrhunderts_%28II%29_001.jpg" width="85" height="140" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Chinesischer_Maler_des_11._Jahrhunderts_%